      "text": "On the other hand, it obviously does not have that relation to binary schematisms which characterizes the \"prudentia\" of the Greco-Roman tradition, which in turn determined ancient European semantics until modern times. For these prudentia were about rationality in a quite different meaning, namely, advice for behavior confronted with a difference – be it the difference between past and future, be it the moral difference, i.e., the possibility that others can act both well and badly. Prudentials, then, can relate to the time dimension and the social dimension in a very different meaning than wisdoms, and can therefore be considered, in an evolutionary sense, as \"preadaptive advances\" for novel rationalities."
